 From the cases, 142 are Kenyans while 71 are foreigners; 101 are males and 112 are females, while the youngest is a 1-year-old and the oldest is 92 years old. Total confirmed positive cases are now 327,145 while the cumulative tests so far conducted are 3,703,840. In terms of county distribution, Nairobi recorded the highest cases with 139. Kitui followed with 44, Kilifi 13, Nyeri 8, Mombasa 4, Kiambu 3, Embu and Siaya 1 case each. A total of 46 patients are currently admitted to various health facilities countrywide, while 1,779 are under the Home-Based Isolation and Care program. “5 patients are in the Intensive Care Unit (ICU) or on supplemental oxygen while 3 are in the general wards. No patient is in the High Dependency Unit (HDU).” Health Cabinet Secretary Mutahi Kagwe said in a statement on Monday. CS Kagwe noted that 150 patients recovered from the disease, 135 of them from Home-Based Isolation and Care while 15 are from various health facilities across the nation. This pushes the total recoveries to 319,669. No death was recorded; cumulative fatalities now stand at 5,651. In the vaccination front, a total of 18,442,246 vaccines had been administered across the country as of June 12, 2022. “Another 1,450,149 are doses administered to those between 15 to 17 years, 37,541 are below 15 years but above 12 years while 377,958 are booster doses,” said CS Kagwe. Proportion of adults fully vaccinated was 31.3%. The Government is working towards vaccinating a targeted population of 27,246,033.